There are some good counterpoints to this argument. For one, some may believe happiness comes from our own self-centered pursuit of our goals. After all, we tend to feel good after achieving something. However, I'd argue this is not true happiness. We may feel good for a moment but it is nothing but a brief dopamine hit. It would be like saying on is genuinely happy because they just had a bowl of icecream. It is important not to confuse hedonistic pleasures with happiness and we will find that when we are on our deathbed, we often don't recount how much money we've made or the material possessions we've had. We usually look back on our experiences and the most memorable of those experiences will be with other people. If those experiences were had with people who were genuine and happy, as opposed to greedy and self-centered, it stands to reason that we'd feel better off for being around those kinds of people. Another point people may bring up is that they cannot afford to have a grand standing goal of making others happy. They need to focus on theirselves and their own survival. This is a valid point and I am a firm believer that one cannot help others until they help theirselves. That being said, one may find that the best way to help theirself is to help others. It is also the case that ideally being in a position to be unable to help others is a temporary state afterwhich we should seek to help others. This I believe will lead to the greatest benefit, both materially and in terms of being happy. \n\nTo be happy is probably life's central goal. If we boiled down all of our decisions and tried to determine to what end do they lead, I believe a word like happiness or fulfillment would be the chief motivator. Many believe that in order to be happy then they must strive for their own goals and own successes and that they cannot afford to waste time on other people. However, I believe that true happiness lies in helping others and creating a strong, loving global community.
